<p><b>Marriage</b> is a legally sanctioned union, usually between a man and a woman. In a <a href="/wiki/Monogamous" title="Monogamous" class="mw-redirect">monogamous</a> marriage, there are two partners, while a <a href="/wiki/Polygamous" title="Polygamous" class="mw-redirect">polygamous</a> marriage includes more than two. The marital union may also be called <b>matrimony</b> or <b>wedlock</b>, while the ceremony that marks its beginning is a <a href="/wiki/Wedding" title="Wedding">wedding</a>.</p>
<p>Historically, marriage was about children, property and inheritance. Marriage for love is a recent concept. The anthropology handbook <i><a href="/wiki/Notes_and_Queries" title="Notes and Queries">Notes and Queries</a></i> defines marriage as, "a union of a man and a woman such that children of the woman are recognized as legitimate by both parents."<sup id="cite_ref-Notes_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Notes-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> More recent research disputes the idea that marriage is motivated by a desire to legitimize the status of children. A man's need for assurance as to the paternity of his children makes him willing to provide something of value to a woman or her kin in exchange for sexual control.</p>
<p>Marriage may take <a href="/wiki/Types_of_marriages" title="Types of marriages">many forms</a>: for example, a union between one man and one woman as <a href="/wiki/Husband" title="Husband">husband</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wife" title="Wife">wife</a> is a <a href="/wiki/Monogamy" title="Monogamy">monogamous</a> <a href="/wiki/Heterosexuality" title="Heterosexuality">heterosexual</a> marriage; <a href="/wiki/Polygamy" title="Polygamy">polygamy</a>&#160;– in which a person takes more than one <a href="/wiki/Spouse" title="Spouse">spouse</a>&#160;– which includes, <a href="/wiki/Polygyny" title="Polygyny">polygyny</a> in which a man takes more than one wife, and <a href="/wiki/Polyandry" title="Polyandry">polyandry</a> in which a woman takes more than one husband have been common in some <a href="/wiki/Society" title="Society">societies</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Murdoch_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Murdoch-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Recently, some jurisdictions<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> and <a href="/wiki/Religious_denomination" title="Religious denomination">denominations</a><sup id="cite_ref-pewforum_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pewforum-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-NYT_UCC_SSM_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT_UCC_SSM-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-UUA_BGLT_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-UUA_BGLT-5" title=""><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup> have begun to recognize <a href="/wiki/Same-sex_marriage" title="Same-sex marriage">same-sex marriage</a>, uniting people of the <a href="/wiki/Homosexuality" title="Homosexuality">same sex</a>.</p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Universal_Declaration_of_Human_Rights" title="Universal Declaration of Human Rights">Universal Declaration of Human Rights</a> declares that "Men and women of full age, without any limitation due to race, nationality or religion, have the right to marry and to found a family. They are entitled to equal rights as to marriage, during marriage and at its dissolution. Marriage shall be entered into only with the free and full consent of the intending spouses." The <a href="/wiki/Cairo_Declaration_on_Human_Rights_in_Islam" title="Cairo Declaration on Human Rights in Islam">Cairo Declaration on Human Rights in Islam</a> gives men and women the "right to marriage" regardless of their race, colour or nationality, but not religion.</p>
